<DOC><DOCNO> AP880613-0018 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 0104EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-PollMethod     06-13 0472</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Poll Method,0495</SECOND><HEAD>With PM-Poll-Presidential Choices, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   This Media General-Associated Press poll isbased on telephone interviews April 29-May 8 with 1,204 adults inthe continental United States. The phone numbers were selectedrandomly by computer and interviews were conducted with the adultwho had the most recent birthday.   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in thesample. The poll has a three-point margin of error, meaning theresults theoretically would be within three points of the same 19times out of 20 if every adult American were asked the samequestions. The error margin is larger for subgroups _ five pointsfor Republicans, for example.   There are other sources of potential error in polls, includingthe wording and order of questions. These are the questions andresponses in this poll:   1. Presidents now are limited to two four-year terms in office.Do you think it should be one-six year term, stay at two four-yearterms, be three four-year terms, or four or more four-year terms?   One six-year: 16 percent. Two four-year: 65 percent. Threefour-year: 8 percent. Four or more four-year: 5 percent. None ofthese: 4 percent. Don't know or no answer: 2 percent.   2. If Ronald Reagan could run again, would you vote for him fora third term as president?   Yes: 32 percent. No: 64 percent. Don't know or no answer: 4percent.   3. I'm going to read a few attributes that might be found in acandidate for president. Tell me if each would make you more likelyto vote for that candidate for president, or less likely to votefor that candidate, or if it wouldn't matter.   a. A woman. More likely: 10 percent. Less: 25 percent. Notmatter: 64. DK-NA: 2 percent.   b. A black. More likely: 5 percent. Less: 27 percent. Notmatter: 66 percent. DK-NA: 3 percent.   4. Would you be more likely or less likely to vote for a ticketthat has a woman candidate for vice president, or wouldn't itmatter?   More likely: 10 percent. Less: 14 percent. Not matter: 75percent. DK-NA: 1 percent.   5. Would you be more likely or less likely to vote for a ticketthat has a black candidate for vice president, or wouldn't itmatter?   More likely: 6 percent. Less: 18 percent. Not matter: 75percent. DK-NA: 1 percent.   6. Do you think it matters who's elected president?   Yes: 89 percent. No: 9 percent. DK-NA: 2 percent.   7. Would you want the job of president?   Yes: 11 percent. No: 89 percent. DK-NA: 1 percent.   8. Would you want your child to grow up to be president?   Yes: 41 percent. No: 46 percent. DK-NA: 13 percent.   9. Do you think it's possible your child could grow up to bepresident?   Yes: 59 percent. No: 34 percent. DK-NA: 8 percent.</TEXT></DOC>